   </xocs:meta><xocs:serial-item xmlns:xoe="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/xoe/dtd">
      <article xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/ja/dtd" docsubtype="fla" version="5.7" xml:lang="en">
         <item-info>
            <jid>YJEMA</jid>
            <aid>126981</aid>
            <ce:article-number>126981</ce:article-number>
            <ce:pii>S0301-4797(25)02957-3</ce:pii>
            <ce:doi>10.1016/j.jenvman.2025.126981</ce:doi>
            <ce:copyright type="other" year="2025">The Authors</ce:copyright>
         </item-info>
         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="fig1">
               <ce:label>Fig. 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0010" view="all">Effects of changes in (a) <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, (b) <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, and (c) <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> on the Chapman-Richards growth function (Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd4" id="crosref1050">(4)</ce:cross-ref>). <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> is a scale parameter for carbon density and an asymptotic upper limit. <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> is a scale parameter for stand age and the rapidity of relative carbon accumulation to the maximum. <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> determines the shape of the growth curve and negatively affects the growth rate in the initial phase of forest growth.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0020">Fig. 1</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479725029573/gr1"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig2">
               <ce:label>Fig. 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0015" view="all">Schematic illustration of the model structures. In this study, growth functions at the national, regional, prefecture, and stand levels were defined. The Markov random field model was applied to express the spatial structure of the model parameters at the prefecture level.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0025">Fig. 2</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479725029573/gr2"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig3">
               <ce:label>Fig. 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0020" view="all">(a) Relationship between forest carbon density and stand age at the national level, and (b) forest carbon density and (c) forest carbon accumulation rate divided by tree organs. (a) Red and blue points represent the NFI and the LS data, respectively. A solid line indicates the medians with a gray band showing 95 % credible intervals in the NFI-LS model. A dashed line is the regression curve for the YT model. (b) Carbon allocation to leaves and branches, stems, and roots was calculated using Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd1" id="crosref1055">(1)</ce:cross-ref>. The sum for each organ equals the solid line in the panel above (a). (c) Curves denote were derived by differentiating the Richards function (Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd4" id="crosref1060">(4)</ce:cross-ref>) and the <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                           <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                           <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> model (Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd3" id="crosref1065">(3)</ce:cross-ref>) with stand age. (c, d) Vertical dotted, dashed, and solid lines indicate stand ages at the onset of the young, mature, and old-growth stages for each organ, respectively. The age at the onset of the old-growth stage for stems is not shown because of an out-of-range value.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0030">Fig. 3</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479725029573/gr3"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig4">
               <ce:label>Fig. 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0025">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0025" view="all">(a) A Japan map showing regions, (b) the Richards functions estimated in the NFI-LS model, and (c) posterior distributions of the estimated parameters of the functions at the regional level. Regions are represented by the same color in all panels. (b) Solid lines mean the medians with bands showing 50 % credible intervals for each region. (c) Ranges of boxes and whiskers indicate 50 % and 95 % credible intervals, respectively, in the model. Different letters mean significant differences, and n.s. denotes no significant difference among the regions.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0035">Fig. 4</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479725029573/gr4"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig5">
               <ce:label>Fig. 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0030">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0030" view="all">Geographical distribution of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan and medians of estimated parameters for (a) <mml:math altimg="si122.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, (b) <mml:math altimg="si123.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, and (c) <mml:math altimg="si124.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math> at the prefecture level. Estimates are indicated with the same colors within each prefecture.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0040">Fig. 5</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479725029573/gr5"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig6">
               <ce:label>Fig. 6</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0035">
                  <ce:simple-para id="fspara0035" view="all">Predictions of (a) area and (b) carbon stock for <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests in Japan. (a, b) Based on the six scenarios, numerical simulations were conducted for the period from 2022 to 2112. A vertical dashed line indicates 2022, and a horizontal dashed line denotes an estimate in 2022 based on the YT model. Red and blue lines represent estimates based on NFI-LS model (Cases 2.0, 2.1, and 2.2) and YT model (Cases 1.0, 1.1, and 1.2), respectively. Among them, dashed, solid, and dotted lines indicate scenarios with no forest management (Cases 1.0 and 2.0), the current management conditions (i.e., 28.26 Mm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> for <mml:math altimg="si108.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, and 36.8 % for <mml:math altimg="si118.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">p</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>) (Cases 1.1 and 2.1), and active reforestation (i.e., 28.26 Mm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> for <mml:math altimg="si108.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, and 100 % for <mml:math altimg="si118.svg">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">p</mml:mi>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>) (Cases 1.2 and 2.2), respectively (see <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref1070">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). Bands around lines show 95 % credible intervals.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0045">Fig. 6</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link locator="gr6" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0301479725029573/gr6"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:table xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" id="tbl1" frame="topbot" colsep="0" rowsep="0">
               <ce:label>Table 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0040">
                  <ce:simple-para id="tspara0010" view="all">Data source for the Richards function, yield of stem volume, and reforestation rate for different scenarios simulating the future carbon stock in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text role="short" id="alttext0050">Table 1</ce:alt-text>
               <tgroup cols="4">
                  <colspec colnum="1" colname="col1"/>
                  <colspec colnum="2" colname="col2"/>
                  <colspec colnum="3" colname="col3"/>
                  <colspec colnum="4" colname="col4"/>
                  <thead>
                     <row rowsep="1" valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Scenario</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Data for the Richards function</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Yield of stem volume (Mm<sup loc="post">3</sup> yr<sup loc="post">−1</sup>)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Reforestation rate (%)</entry>
                     </row>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">Case 1.0</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">YT<cross-ref refid="tbl1fna" id="crosref1075">
                              <sup loc="post">a</sup>
                           </cross-ref>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">Case 1.1</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">YT</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">28.26</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">36.8</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">Case 1.2</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">YT</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">28.26</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">100</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">Case 2.0</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">NFI<cross-ref refid="tbl1fnb" id="crosref1080">
                              <sup loc="post">b</sup>
                           </cross-ref> + LS<cross-ref refid="tbl1fnc" id="crosref1085">
                              <sup loc="post">c</sup>
                           </cross-ref>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">Case 2.1</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="left">NFI + LS</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">28.26</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">36.8</entry>
