               <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Data will be made available on request.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec1" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0035">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Forest ecosystems are major carbon sinks that significantly affect global biological and physical cycles (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0040">Keenan and Williams, 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib59" id="crosref0045">Pan et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>). Forests absorb carbon dioxide (CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>) from the atmosphere and store carbon resources mainly in soil organic matter and tree biomass for long periods. In global terrestrial ecosystems, forest ecosystems contribute up to 50 % of net primary production (NPP) and contain up to 45 % of carbon resources accumulated in their leaves, stems, and belowground parts (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib7" id="crosref0050">Bonan, 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib70" id="crosref0055">Sha et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Given that forest ecosystems comprise plant, animal, and microbial populations, forest carbon assimilation through biochemical reactions is driven by various biotic (e.g., species composition and symbiotic organisms) and abiotic (e.g., meteorological and edaphic conditions) factors (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0060">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib5" id="crosref0065">Begović et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). Understanding and predicting biomass growth patterns in various forest types with consideration of such biotic and abiotic factors are needed to understand carbon dynamics in forest ecosystems across a broad distribution worldwide.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">Estimation of forest biomass resources is essential not only in the context of ecological aspects to understand material cycles (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib36" id="crosref0070">Keith et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib60" id="crosref0075">Pan et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>) but also in the context of social issues such as providing a scientific consensus that guarantees carbon credits, with which governments and companies deal to optimize the global carbon balance (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib18" id="crosref0080">Fahey et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib24" id="crosref0085">Gren and Aklilu, 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib83" id="crosref0090">van der Gaast et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). In order to promote social and environmental activities to achieve carbon neutrality, there is an urgent need to accurately evaluate the carbon accumulation capacity of forests. One role of researchers in forest science is to provide accurate estimations of annual carbon accumulation and sequestration in forest ecosystems and optimization of forest management to maintain forest resources in the future. This information assists governments to make decisions for building a sustainable society in relation to resource cycling and for mitigation of climate change caused by global warming (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib72" id="crosref0095">Stocker et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). For these policy issues, prediction of forest carbon stocks and their future changes is required, with consideration of the degree of uncertainty.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">Several methods have been developed to estimate the carbon stock in forests. Generally, the forest carbon stock at a given time point can be estimated from direct measurements of individual tree sizes, such as diameter and height within a certain stand area, and converting the data to mass-based metrics (e.g., stem volume and biomass) with allometric equations (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib10" id="crosref0100">Chave et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib84" id="crosref0105">Vashum, 2012</ce:cross-ref>). Individual tree metrics can then be combined with measures of stem density to estimate total carbon densities. Forest carbon density then strongly depends on the stand age as individual tree size and stem densities both vary considerably with stand age, especially in even-aged forests. Forest biomass estimates must be defined as a function of stand age since plantation establishment or a catastrophic disturbance, such as a wildfire (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0110">Besnard et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>), to calculate the future forest carbon stocks. However, the function and its accuracy in estimating forest biomass are generally species-specific and vulnerable to decreasing evenness of stand age. Given variability in growth rates and carbon densities among species, it is essential to establish species-specific relationships between forest carbon stock and stand age to evaluate the current carbon stock in forests and to predict temporal changes in the future. Forest measurement data covering a broad range of stand ages for a given species are therefore crucial to derive accurate relationships with consideration of uncertainty attributable to the potential contribution of old-growth forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib25" id="crosref0115">Gundersen et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0120">Luyssaert et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>) and changes in forest management expected in each country and region.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">Forest biomass accumulation with age has been evaluated worldwide. The accumulation capacity is generally lower in the boreal biome and higher in temperate and tropical regions (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib59" id="crosref0125">Pan et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib62" id="crosref0130">Pregitzer and Euskirchen, 2004</ce:cross-ref>). Within each biome, the accumulation patterns have been differentiated with forest type categories based on species composition, climate, and geography (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0135">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib65" id="crosref0140">Repo et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Notably, climate change may modify carbon accumulation patterns in various forest types at a continental scale (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0145">McMahon et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib86" id="crosref0150">Zhu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Thus, forest biomass depends not only on stand age but also on changes in growth environments, species composition, and stand structure. In Japan, forest stem volume and biomass are often estimated from stand age, usually based on yield tables representing the relationship between forest age and stem volume that were established several decades ago. However, the uncertainty of stem volume estimates based on yield tables has been noted as a result of severe changes in environmental conditions and social background (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0155">Egusa et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Potential errors in yield table-derived estimates have been specifically attributed to the following factors: 1) the lack of data for old-aged forests, 2) improvement in forest growth environments owing to climatic changes in recent decades, and 3) lack of thinning due to a decline in timber demand and the resulting shift in forestry management practices. Considering these factors, there is a pressing need to improve outdated forest measurement data and to reconstruct equations to improve predictions of forest carbon stock changes with stand age considering older and more mature forests. Hereafter, we explicitly consider old-growth forests as forests in a biomass saturation stage beyond the maturation phase (e.g., stand ages with forest biomass more than 95 % of the maximum), while old-aged forests merely indicate forests in later stages of development (e.g., more than 50 years old for plantations) regardless of history in forestry practices.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">It should be noted that direct measurement data in old-growth forests are limited compared with those for young and mature forests. Since the end of the Second World War, the use of forest resources has declined because of the increase in use of fossil fuels. Therefore, the average forest age in Japan and other countries has increased owing to reduced frequency of harvesting (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0160">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib14" id="crosref0165">Egusa et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib29" id="crosref0170">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023a</ce:cross-ref>). In such situations, it is essential to evaluate the biomass growth of old-aged forests in addition to understanding the influence of global warming (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib86" id="crosref0175">Zhu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Moreover, the growth potential of old-aged forests can be significantly affected by past disturbance and forestry practices, which causes substantial uncertainty when estimating carbon stock in these older forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib5" id="crosref0180">Begović et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib25" id="crosref0185">Gundersen et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Previous studies conducted in diverse regions across the world suggest that a re-evaluation of the carbon assimilation rate in old-aged forests is needed (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0190">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib5" id="crosref0195">Begović et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib25" id="crosref0200">Gundersen et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0205">Luyssaert et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>), and that prediction of future forest resources with consideration of old-growth forests is a fundamental challenge.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">Forests cover 68.4 % of the land area in Japan, which is one of the highest percentages of forest area among all countries (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib21" id="crosref0210">FAO, 2020</ce:cross-ref>) and constitutes a significant proportion of the total forest carbon stock in east Asia (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib20" id="crosref0215">Fang et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>). Recent findings indicate that the forest carbon stock in Japan may have been significantly underestimated (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0220">Egusa et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), and therefore, its re-evaluation is needed. The most dominant and important forest types for nature landscape, forestry wood production, and carbon accumulation in Japan is <ce:italic>Cryptomeria japonica</ce:italic> D. Don forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0225">Fukuda et al., 2003</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib30" id="crosref0230">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023b</ce:cross-ref>). Surprisingly, the forests of this single species, <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica,</ce:italic> cover 18 % of all forest areas and 44 % of total forest plantation areas in Japan (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib29" id="crosref0235">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023a</ce:cross-ref>). Most <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forest stands are currently approximately 50 years old and transitioning to the old-aged phase, and regeneration of younger stands is not anticipated because of the low afforestation rate (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib29" id="crosref0240">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023a</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib30" id="crosref0245">2023b</ce:cross-ref>). Thus, existing <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests in Japan will likely continue to age with minimal reforestation.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">Meteorological and edaphic factors affect tree growth patterns, regeneration, and their geographical variation. <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> trees are well-known to grow taller and live longer than other tree species in Japan, but the maximum height, ages, and reproductive strategies also depend on the local habitats (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib1" id="crosref0250">Azuma et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0255">Nishizono et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib74" id="crosref0260">Suzuki and Tsukahara, 1987</ce:cross-ref>). Some <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> trees from specific provenances are shade tolerant, which enables their clonal regeneration and seedling recruitment under harsh environments in natural forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib37" id="crosref0265">Kimura et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib58" id="crosref0270">Ota et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib75" id="crosref0275">Tabuchi et al., 1981</ce:cross-ref>). Given that <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests are distributed throughout a broad latitudinal range from boreal to subtropical regions across Japanese archipelago (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0280">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>), meteorological and edaphic factors are likely to strongly influence tree aboveground growth characteristics and belowground nutrient acquisition strategies (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib27" id="crosref0285">Hirano et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0290">Nishizono et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib80" id="crosref0295">Tsumura et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib85" id="crosref0300">Wada et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). As a consequence of intergenerational adaptation, the dominant genotypes of <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> trees differ between west and east populations in Japanese archipelago. The western populations have a relatively high growth rate at an early stage of forest development, whereas the eastern populations grow to a higher maximum stand height. Importantly, these genotypic differences can lead to different stand characteristics, even when grown under the same environmental conditions (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib2" id="crosref0305">Azuma et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib50" id="crosref0310">Nakahata et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>). Geographical variation in forest carbon accumulation attributable to environmental and genotypic factors should therefore be considered to understand and predict patterns of growth in <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">The National Forest Inventory (NFI) data collected by the Japan Forest Agency are among the most comprehensive and reliable data sets for forests across Japan and have enabled improved estimates of national forest resources (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0315">Egusa et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib14" id="crosref0320">2024</ce:cross-ref>). Several studies indicate that forest carbon density and its accumulation rate are larger, compared with that derived from the previous yield tables, in specific old-aged forests of <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic>, evaluated by performing a rigorous ground-based tree census (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib39" id="crosref0325">Kunisaki and Yamazaki, 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib53" id="crosref0330">Nishizono et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>). To evaluate the carbon accumulation capacity of <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests at broader scales and understand how increases in the age of these stands impact their growth and total forest carbon stock, we specifically address the following aims: 1) to estimate carbon accumulation patterns in <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests at the national level using stand-based data obtained from the latest NFI and a survey of the previous literature, 2) to clarify geographical variation in growth patterns by modeling growth functions at the regional, prefecture, and stand levels with hierarchical structures, and 3) to predict the future carbon stock in <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests using the novel growth models developed in this study and considering different forest management scenarios under the current levels of harvesting and reforestation rate.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec2" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0040">Materials and methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0045">Data collection</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">We used the NFI data to estimate the carbon stock in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan and then augmented this data set where data coverage was insufficient, most notably for old-aged forests. Therefore, we conducted an additional literature survey (LS) to compensate for the paucity of data covering a broad range of forest ages from early to old-growth stages. In addition to NFI data providing only a small number of time points for each stand, some LS data provided consecutive growth data over a long period from a specific forest, which enhanced the robustness of estimating forest growth trajectories.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">Japan's NFI is implemented with the aim of obtaining objective forest information at 4 km grid points over the entire land area of Japan using a nationally standardized methodology; the information is necessary to set forestry policy for the promotion of sustainable forest management (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib29" id="crosref0335">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023a</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:inter-ref xlink:href="http://forestbio.jp/" id="intref0010" xlink:type="simple">http://forestbio.jp/</ce:inter-ref>). The survey for the 1st NFI was conducted from 1999 to 2003, and has been repeated at 5 year intervals since. In the survey, size metrics of tree individuals are measured in a consistent circular plot area of each grid point, and this was then repeated for the same plot area at each time interval unless the plots were inaccessible or catastrophically disturbed. The most recently collected data, forming the 4th NFI based on field surveys performed in 2014–2018, were released in February 2023. Importantly, among the four NFI surveys, the most recent two data sets (i.e., the 3rd and 4th NFI data) are the most reliable owing to methodological improvements such as the provision of technical training for investigators and supervision of data quality by experts. Therefore, we used the 3rd and 4th NFI data (hereafter, NFI3 and NFI4), obtained from the 2009–2013 and the 2014–2018 field surveys, respectively, for data analyses. First, we extracted data comprising forest stem volume (m<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), stand age (yr), prefecture number, latitude, and longitude for forest plots dominated by <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> from NFI3 and NFI4. The number of forest plots dominated by <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> in NFI4 is 2645 (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0340">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>) out of a total ca. 15,000 plots, and 1996 plots within the <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forest plots have the same plot identification as used in NFI3, thus those plots were consecutively surveyed from NFI3. The consecutive plots were mainly used for subsequent analyses so that we could evaluate growth functions for each forest stand with consideration of growth trends determined by two time point data between NFI3 and NFI4. Note that some plot data potentially have been influenced by forestry practices or meteorological disturbance because the NFI survey was performed regardless of the forest history.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">In addition to the NFI data, published literature was reviewed to extract data on <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan. The literature survey was conducted through the online Google Scholar platform by searching academic journals and library sources using combinations of the following keywords: “Japanese cedar”, “<ce:italic>Cryptomeria japonica</ce:italic>”, “stem volume”, “biomass”, “carbon stock”, “stand age”, “growth function”, and “old-growth forest” in English and Japanese. Through the literature survey, data sets comprising location information, stand age (yr), and either stem volume (m<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), biomass (Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), or carbon density (MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) at the stand level were compiled. If data were described only in figures without textual information, WebPlotDigitizer (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib67" id="crosref0345">Rohatgi, 2019</ce:cross-ref>) was used to extract values from the figure images. The data were based on field studies that were mostly conducted in public forests where resource monitoring and management practices have been implemented for scientific objectives (e.g., <ce:cross-ref refid="bib55" id="crosref0350">Nishizono et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib78" id="crosref0355">Tange et al., 1994</ce:cross-ref>). Ultimately, 59 literature sources, including peer-reviewed research articles and bulletins from universities and research institutes, provided 1178 data points for forest carbon density and age from 426 forest stands distributed across 30 prefectures (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0360">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>). Many of the forest stands selected in the LS include consecutive time point data within each stand.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">To compare a growth function (NFI-LS model) modeled with the NFI and LS data (hereafter, NFI-LS data) with that modeled using outdated forest data, we additionally compiled data sets for total stem volume (m<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup>) and forest area (ha) of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests for each stand age class based on the outdated yield tables (YT data) previously released by the Japan Forestry Agency (Japan Forestry Agency: Current status of forest resources). These data sets were established several decades ago by direct field measurements but likely underestimate the current forest carbon stocks (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0365">Egusa et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Stand stem volume per area (m<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) was calculated by dividing the total stem volume by forest area for each age class, and then converted into carbon biomass per unit area (MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib20" id="crosref0370">Fang et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>) to derive an overall relationship between forest carbon density and stand age for <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests. This manipulation was conducted for four data sets released in 1981, 1986, 1991, and 1995, and these were then averaged and used for subsequent analysis of a growth model, i.e., the yield table model (YT model).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0050">Estimation of forest carbon density from stem volume</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">Forest carbon density (<mml:math altimg="si1.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>; MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) was calculated from forest stem volume per area (<mml:math altimg="si2.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>V</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>; m<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) in the NFI-LS data as follows:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd1">
                              <ce:label>(1)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si3.svg" alttext="Equation 1.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>V</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>
                        <ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd2">
                              <ce:label>(2)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si4.svg" alttext="Equation 2.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>W</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>D</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                      <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>R</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si5.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (MgC m<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>) is a conversion factor to convert forest stem volume to forest carbon density, <mml:math altimg="si6.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>W</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>D</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is wood density (0.314 Mg m<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>), <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is biomass expansion factor, <mml:math altimg="si8.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>R</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the ratio of belowground biomass to aboveground biomass (0.25), and <mml:math altimg="si9.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the carbon content in conifers (0.51 gC g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>). The values for <mml:math altimg="si6.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>W</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>D</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si8.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>R</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si9.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> were obtained from the "National Greenhouse Gas Inventory Report of Japan 2022" (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib46" id="crosref0380">Ministry of the Environment, 2022</ce:cross-ref>). <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the ratio of aboveground biomass (leaves, branches, and stem) to stem biomass, and was modeled using <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> from the LS data (e.g., <ce:cross-ref refid="bib76" id="crosref0385">Tange, 2018</ce:cross-ref>) as a function of stand age (<mml:math altimg="si10.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>; yr) (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0390">Fig. S2</ce:cross-ref>) as follows (see “Statistical analysis”):<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd3">
                              <ce:label>(3)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si11.svg" alttext="Equation 3.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msup>
                                                   <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi>b</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msup>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>exp</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>a</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si12.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>a</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si13.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>b</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are estimated parameters. In the LS data, if the literature provided <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> of itself or aboveground biomass data enabling us to calculate that, we used the provided <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> to estimate the <mml:math altimg="si1.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Regarding the NFI data, forest plots that seemed to have aberrant <mml:math altimg="si1.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> values, likely due to data input error, were eliminated from the original data for subsequent model analyses (“Modeling of forest carbon density with age”), by using thresholds of 99 % intervals for probability distributions for the data (see “Supplementary Materials” and <ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0395">Fig. S3</ce:cross-ref>). After this manipulation, data from 1432 forest plots in both NFI3 and NF4 were retained (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0400">Fig. S4</ce:cross-ref>). However, as an exception, data for one plot in Osaka prefecture from NFI4 were added, because this prefecture was the only one with no consecutive plots between NFI3 and NFI4. Ultimately, 2865 plot data for <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests (i.e., 1432 plots × 2 time points + 1 plot) were retained as the NFI data used for the following analyses.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.3" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0055">Modeling of forest carbon density with age</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">Model estimation was conducted to evaluate carbon accumulation patterns with stand age up to and beyond the typical mature stage using the NFI-LS data. The patterns were modeled based on the Chapman-Richards growth function (hereafter, the Richards function) as follows (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib61" id="crosref0405">Pienaar and Turnbull, 1973</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib66" id="crosref0410">Richards, 1959</ce:cross-ref>):<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd4">
                              <ce:label>(4)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si14.svg" alttext="Equation 4.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:msup>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>exp</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mfrac>
                                                      <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mfrac>
                                                </mml:msup>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si15.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the mean forest carbon density (MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) and is defined as a growth function <mml:math altimg="si16.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> of stand age <mml:math altimg="si10.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are parameters of the growth function at the national level in Japan. <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is a scale parameter for carbon density and an asymptotic upper limit of <mml:math altimg="si15.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is a scale parameter for stand age and the rapidity of relative carbon accumulation to the maximum. <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> determines the shape of the growth curve and negatively affects the growth rate in the initial phase of forest growth (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0415">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig1"/>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">We further formulated the Richards functions for each region (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0420">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig2"/>) as<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd5">
                              <ce:label>(5)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si20.svg" alttext="Equation 5.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msup>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>exp</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:msub>
                                                                  <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                                               </mml:msub>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                                  <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mfrac>
                                                      <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mfrac>
                                                </mml:msup>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where, <mml:math altimg="si21.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is mean forest carbon density (MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) and is defined as a growth function <mml:math altimg="si22.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si23.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si24.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si25.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are the parameters at a regional level corresponding to <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, respectively. <mml:math altimg="si26.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is a vector <mml:math altimg="si27.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, where <mml:math altimg="si28.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>8</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, representing an index of the regions in Japan with native <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0425">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">Growth characteristics of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests are possibly differentiated with greater local and topographic variation within each region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0430">Nishizono et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib79" id="crosref0435">Tsumura, 2023</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, we established a hierarchical Bayesian model based on the Richards function in which model parameters at the national (<mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) and the regional (<mml:math altimg="si29.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si30.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si31.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) levels were hierarchized into prefecture and forest stand levels (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0440">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). Our model derived in this study is regarded as a Markov random field model, which considers the spatial structure of the parameters. To localize the model parameters, the Richards functions at the prefecture level were defined as<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd6">
                              <ce:label>(6)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si32.svg" alttext="Equation 6.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msup>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>exp</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:msub>
                                                                  <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                               </mml:msub>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                                  <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mfrac>
                                                      <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mfrac>
                                                </mml:msup>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si33.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the mean forest carbon density (MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) as in Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd5" id="crosref0445">(5)</ce:cross-ref>, and is defined as a growth function <mml:math altimg="si34.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si35.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si36.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si37.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are the parameters at the prefecture level corresponding to <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, respectively. <mml:math altimg="si38.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is a vector <mml:math altimg="si39.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>J</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, where <mml:math altimg="si40.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>J</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>46</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, representing an index of prefectures excluding Okinawa where native <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests are not included in the NFI (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0450">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>). The parameters at the national level, <mml:math altimg="si41.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and those at the regional level, <mml:math altimg="si42.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rng</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, were then calculated as area-weighted means of the parameters at the prefecture level, <mml:math altimg="si43.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, respectively. Accordingly, <mml:math altimg="si44.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si45.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rng</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> were defined by the following equations:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd7">
                              <ce:label>(7)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si46.svg" alttext="Equation 7.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mfrac>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:munderover>
                                                         <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mi>J</mml:mi>
                                                      </mml:munderover>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:munderover>
                                                         <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mi>J</mml:mi>
                                                      </mml:munderover>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfrac>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>
                        <ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd8">
                              <ce:label>(8)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si47.svg" alttext="Equation 8.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mtext>rng</mml:mtext>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mfrac>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:munderover>
                                                         <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>J</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:munderover>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:munderover>
                                                         <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>J</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:munderover>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfrac>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si48.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (%) is the percentage of forest plot numbers among prefectures based on the NFI4 data (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0455">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>). <mml:math altimg="si49.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si50.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>J</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> mean the first and last prefecture indexes for each region <mml:math altimg="si26.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, respectively. In addition, we assumed that each <mml:math altimg="si51.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is similar to that in adjoining prefectures. In other words, the <mml:math altimg="si51.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> between adjoining prefectures does not differ significantly from each other, which was applied by introducing a stochastic process based on the normal probability distribution as follows:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd9">
                              <ce:label>(9)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si52.svg" alttext="Equation 9.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>T</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo>∼</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>N</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>a</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">X</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si53.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">X</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mtext>Cdm</mml:mtext>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">k</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">m</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the standard deviation of the normal distribution, either corresponding to <mml:math altimg="si43.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si54.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>T</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si55.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are indexes representing the adjacency relationship among prefectures, in which <mml:math altimg="si56.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>N</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si57.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>N</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>45</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0460">Table S2</ce:cross-ref>). This manipulation increases the likelihood in the model when the parameters assumed more similar values between adjoining prefectures.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">Furthermore, the Richards functions for each forest stand, <mml:math altimg="si58.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, were modeled using data samples from each consecutive plot in the NFI-LS data as follows:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd10">
                              <ce:label>(10)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si59.svg" alttext="Equation 10.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msup>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>exp</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:msub>
                                                                  <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                               </mml:msub>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                                  <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mfrac>
                                                      <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:msub>
                                                            <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mfrac>
                                                </mml:msup>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si60.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the mean forest carbon density (MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) and is defined as a growth function <mml:math altimg="si61.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si62.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si63.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si64.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are the parameters at the stand level corresponding to <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, respectively. <mml:math altimg="si65.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is a vector <mml:math altimg="si66.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>L</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, where <mml:math altimg="si67.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>L</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>1859</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, representing an index of the stands included in the NFI-LS data. The parameters at the stand level, expressed as <mml:math altimg="si68.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, conform to the normal distribution with mean parameters of <mml:math altimg="si43.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, as follows:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd11">
                              <ce:label>(11)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si69.svg" alttext="Equation 11.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo>∼</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>N</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>a</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mi>f</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mi>d</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">X</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si70.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">X</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mtext>Cdm</mml:mtext>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">k</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>σ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">m</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the standard deviation of the normal distribution, either corresponding to <mml:math altimg="si43.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>X</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si71.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>f</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>d</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>l</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is a vector with a length of 1859 and accords with the prefecture index for each stand.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">Next, we describe the observation model, which describes the data generation processes between the observation variables <mml:math altimg="si72.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> from the NFI-LS data and the latent variables <mml:math altimg="si60.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> defined with the aforementioned Richards functions. It was assumed that <mml:math altimg="si72.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> follows the gamma probability distribution where <mml:math altimg="si60.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the mean parameter defined as<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd12">
                              <ce:label>(12)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si73.svg" alttext="Equation 12.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo>∼</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>G</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>a</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>a</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si74.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si75.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are the shape and rate parameters of the gamma distribution, and <mml:math altimg="si76.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is an index of the observation variables (<mml:math altimg="si77.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">}</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si78.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>4043</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>). <mml:math altimg="si74.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is defined as <mml:math altimg="si79.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">·</mml:mo>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> given that the mean parameter <mml:math altimg="si60.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> of the gamma distribution is determined by <mml:math altimg="si80.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">/</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. As a characteristic of the gamma distribution, it forms the exponential distribution if <mml:math altimg="si81.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">≤</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. However, as it is unlikely that forest biomass is distributed exponentially even in young forests, we defined <mml:math altimg="si75.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> as<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd13">
                              <ce:label>(13)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si82.svg" alttext="Equation 13.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>θ</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msup>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi>λ</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msup>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mfrac>
                                                   <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">[</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>p</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">]</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfrac>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si83.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>θ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (<mml:math altimg="si84.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mn>0</mml:mn>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">&lt;</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>θ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) and <mml:math altimg="si85.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>λ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (<mml:math altimg="si86.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">−</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">&lt;</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>λ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) are the estimated parameters for <mml:math altimg="si87.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. This forces <mml:math altimg="si88.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">&gt;</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> enabling the gamma distribution to be unimodal with any <mml:math altimg="si60.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> values. In this observation model, <mml:math altimg="si83.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>θ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si85.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>λ</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are the only estimated parameters, and <mml:math altimg="si89.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si87.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>std</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are the transformed parameters.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">The parameters in the present model were estimated using a Bayesian approach. Posterior distributions of the parameters were generated using the Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC) method, a type of Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) method (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib8" id="crosref0465">Carlin and Chib, 1995</ce:cross-ref>). Before the MCMC simulation, weakly informative prior distributions and conditions were given to parameters to enhance the sampling efficiency (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0470">Table S3</ce:cross-ref>). In the MCMC simulation, four parallel MCMC chains were run with 10,000 iterations that were retained, including an initial warmup of 2000 iterations. For each chain, the simulation samples were thinned to 20 % to obtain samples as posterior distributions (i.e., 6400 samples for each parameter estimate). The convergence of the MCMC sampling was assessed using the criterion <mml:math altimg="si90.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mover accent="true">
                                 <mml:mi>R</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>ˆ</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mover>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">&lt;</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>1.1</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib23" id="crosref0475">Gelman et al., 1995</ce:cross-ref>). The MCMC method was performed using Stan (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib9" id="crosref0480">Carpenter et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>), a probabilistic programming language, using the Rstan interface of the R statistical software (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib64" id="crosref0485">R Development Core Team, 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.4" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0060">Calculation of onset ages of forest development stages</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">To evaluate the onset ages of forest development stages quantitatively using the Richards functions at the national and regional levels, we defined the stages of early, young, mature, and old-growth forests according to the criteria used in the previous studies (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0490">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib68" id="crosref0495">Salas-Eljatib et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). The early stage ranges from the beginning of the forest growth to the onset of the young stage, which is determined as the stand age when the carbon accumulation rate (<mml:math altimg="si91.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>d</mml:mi>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">/</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>d</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>; <ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0500">Eq. S(1)</ce:cross-ref>) reaches its maximum. The onset of the mature stage is the age when the carbon accumulation rate averaged over the stand age (<mml:math altimg="si92.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">/</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>; <ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0505">Eq. S(2)</ce:cross-ref>) reaches its maximum. The old-growth stage begins from the age when <mml:math altimg="si15.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> reaches 95 % of the asymptotic upper limit in the Richards function (<mml:math altimg="si93.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mn>0.95</mml:mn>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">·</mml:mo>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>). In addition, these calculations of onset ages were conducted for carbon accumulation patterns of leaves and branches (<mml:math altimg="si94.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>leaf</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>), stems (<mml:math altimg="si95.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>stem</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>), and roots (<mml:math altimg="si96.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>root</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>), respectively. Equations for carbon density, carbon accumulation rate, and mean carbon accumulation rate over stand age for each living biomass are given according to the definitions of <mml:math altimg="si5.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si97.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (see “Supplementary Materials”).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.5" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.5</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0065">Prediction of forest carbon stock in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests in Japan</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">Predictions of future carbon stock in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests were simulated from 2022 to 2112 using the Richards functions estimated either with the YT data (YT model) or the NFI-LS data (NFI-LS model). The total carbon stock in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan can be estimated from the forest area for each stand age and the relationship between stand age and forest carbon density (i.e., the Richards function). Temporal changes in forest area for each stand age until 2112 were calculated with a first-order wave equation as follows:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd14">
                              <ce:label>(14)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si98.svg" alttext="Equation 14.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mfrac>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo>∂</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo>∂</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfrac>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mfrac>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo>∂</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mo>∂</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfrac>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si99.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the A.D. year (yr), and <mml:math altimg="si100.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si101.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are the existing forest area and cutting forest area, respectively, for stand age <mml:math altimg="si10.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> in year <mml:math altimg="si99.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si101.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> was expressed by multiplying <mml:math altimg="si100.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> by the harvest rate <mml:math altimg="si102.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> as follows:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd15">
                              <ce:label>(15)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si103.svg" alttext="Equation 15.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>However, <mml:math altimg="si102.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> changes with year and stand age were further defined as<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd16">
                              <ce:label>(16)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si104.svg" alttext="Equation 16.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">/</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si105.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si106.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> are the carbon stock in the cut forests and existing forests, respectively, for stand age <mml:math altimg="si10.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> in year <mml:math altimg="si99.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. <mml:math altimg="si105.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> was further formulated as<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd17">
                              <ce:label>(17)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si107.svg" alttext="Equation 17.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mfrac>
                                                   <mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:munder>
                                                         <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                      </mml:munder>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                                  <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:msup>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                                     <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                                     <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                                  </mml:mrow>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                                  <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                            </mml:msup>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfrac>
                                                <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si108.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (28.26 Mm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) is a constant for the annual cut stem volume in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan, which was estimated as <mml:math altimg="si109.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mml:mo>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>total</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">·</mml:mo>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">/</mml:mo>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>total</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> using <mml:math altimg="si110.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>total</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, the mean annual cut stem volume in all forest types, and the ratio of the mean annual stem volume yield of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> to that of all forest types (<mml:math altimg="si111.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">/</mml:mo>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>total</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) from 2017 to 2021, released by the Japan Forestry Agency (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib30" id="crosref0510">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023b</ce:cross-ref>). Note that <mml:math altimg="si108.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> represents the cut stem volume consisting of that produced for the wood market (<mml:math altimg="si112.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>P</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) and that cut but left in forests. <mml:math altimg="si113.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> was defined by Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd2" id="crosref0515">(2)</ce:cross-ref>. In this study, under the assumption that forests more than 40 years of age are targets for harvest, <mml:math altimg="si114.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> was redefined with Eqs. <ce:cross-refs refid="fd16 fd17" id="crosrefs0010">(16) and (17</ce:cross-refs>) as<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd18">
                              <ce:label>(18)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si115.svg" alttext="Equation 18.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">{</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                                      <mml:mtr>
                                                         <mml:mtd>
                                                            <mml:mfrac>
                                                               <mml:msub>
                                                                  <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                                                  <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                                                               </mml:msub>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:munder>
                                                                     <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                                        <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">≥</mml:mo>
                                                                        <mml:mn>40</mml:mn>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                  </mml:munder>
                                                                  <mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>M</mml:mi>
                                                                        <mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                                           <mml:mrow>
                                                                              <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                                              <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                                           </mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                                        </mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">·</mml:mo>
                                                                        <mml:msup>
                                                                           <mml:mrow>
                                                                              <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                                                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                                                                              <mml:mrow>
                                                                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                                                 <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                                              </mml:mrow>
                                                                           </mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mrow>
                                                                              <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                                              <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                                           </mml:mrow>
                                                                        </mml:msup>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                                  </mml:mrow>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                            </mml:mfrac>
                                                         </mml:mtd>
                                                         <mml:mtd>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mtext>if</mml:mtext>
                                                               <mml:mspace width="0.25em"/>
                                                               <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">≥</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mn>40</mml:mn>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                         </mml:mtd>
                                                      </mml:mtr>
                                                      <mml:mtr>
                                                         <mml:mtd>
                                                            <mml:mn>0</mml:mn>
                                                         </mml:mtd>
                                                         <mml:mtd>
                                                            <mml:mtext>otherwise</mml:mtext>
                                                         </mml:mtd>
                                                      </mml:mtr>
                                                   </mml:mtable>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>
                     </ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">Forest area for age 1 in year <mml:math altimg="si99.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> (<mml:math altimg="si116.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) was calculated as the sum of the harvested forest area in the previous year (<mml:math altimg="si117.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) and reforestation rate (<mml:math altimg="si118.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">p</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) as follows:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="fd19">
                              <ce:label>(19)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si119.svg" alttext="Equation 19.">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtable columnalign="center">
                                       <mml:mtr>
                                          <mml:mtd>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">p</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">h</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                      <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                      <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mtd>
                                       </mml:mtr>
                                    </mml:mtable>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si118.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">p</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is the constant 0.368, which is the mean ratio of reforestation area to harvested area from 2017 to 2021 in Japan (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib30" id="crosref0520">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023b</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">The simulations of forest carbon stock and forest area based on the foregoing calculations were conducted from 2022 to 2112 by setting several assumptions for growth models and management parameters as follows (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0525">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl1"/>): scenarios based on the YT model and the NFI-LS model with no forest management (Cases 1.0 and 2.0, respectively); scenarios based on the YT model and the NFI-LS model with the current management conditions (i.e., 28.26 Mm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> for <mml:math altimg="si108.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and 36.8 % for <mml:math altimg="si118.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">p</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) (Cases 1.1 and 2.1, respectively); and scenarios based on the YT model and the NFI-LS model with active reforestation (i.e., 28.26 Mm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> for <mml:math altimg="si108.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>H</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>CJ</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and 100 % for <mml:math altimg="si118.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>r</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">p</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) (Cases 1.2 and 2.2, respectively).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.6" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.6</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0070">Statistical analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">To assess the YT model, a non-linear least-squares method was applied to examine three parameters (<mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) of the Richards function (Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd4" id="crosref0530">(4)</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">A generalized linear model (GLM) was applied to evaluate the relationship between <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and stand age derived from the LS data. In the GLM, <mml:math altimg="si120.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>E</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>F</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">−</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and stand age were used as the response and explanatory variables, respectively, assuming a gamma error distribution of response variables with the log link function (i.e., Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd3" id="crosref0535">(3)</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">Significant differences among the parameters in the Richards functions estimated with the Bayesian approach were examined based on whether the probability distribution of differences between the posterior MCMC samples overlapping 0 value is less than 5 %.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">These statistical analyses were performed using the R statistical software (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib64" id="crosref0540">R Development Core Team, 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec3" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0075">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0080">Carbon-based growth function for <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">The present study examined the carbon accumulation patterns of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan by applying a hierarchical Bayesian model. The medians of posterior distributions for the model parameters <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> at the national level in the NFI-LS model were 247.1 MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, 0.0321, and 0.469, respectively (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0545">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig3"/>a). In the NFI-LS model, the forest carbon accumulation rate reached a maximum at stand age of 20 yr, and the old-growth forest stage began at 113 yr (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl2" id="crosref0550">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl2"/>). In contrast, <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> were 135.5 MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, 0.0442, and 0.553 in the YT model. According to the YT model, the maximum carbon accumulation rate in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests is reached at age 18 yr, and the old-growth stage begins at 86 yr. In comparison between the NFI-LS and YT models, <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> in the NFI-LS model was significantly 1.82 times higher than that in the YT model, according to 95 % credible intervals (234.1 MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> to 260.5 MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>). Meanwhile, <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> in the NFI-LS model were significantly lower than those in the YT model.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">Throughout forest development, the proportions of leaves and branches, stems, and roots in the carbon density and accumulation rate changed with time (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl2" id="crosref0555">Table 2</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0560">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>). The carbon accumulation rate (<mml:math altimg="si91.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>d</mml:mi>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">/</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>d</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) and mean carbon accumulation rate (<mml:math altimg="si92.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                              </mml:msub>
                              <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">/</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) peaked in the order of leaves and branches, roots, and then stems. Leaves and branches are favored over other organs during early stages of growth, although the carbon accumulation rate became negative after 60 yr. The peak of the mean carbon accumulation rate in stems was at 45 yr, which was 9 yr later than that for whole-tree biomass. Notably, the carbon density in stems reached 95 % of the maximum at 366 yr, which is much later compared with that in whole trees.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0085">Geographical variation in carbon density and growth functions for <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests in Japan</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">In the NFI4 data surveyed from 2014 to 2018, the median carbon density for each prefecture varied between 72.4 MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> and 196.7 MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, while the median stand age ranged from 47 yr to 61 yr, except for Osaka which comprised data for a single plot (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0565">Figure S5 and Figure S6</ce:cross-ref>). Carbon density tended to be higher in plots on the Pacific Ocean side of Japan than on the Sea of Japan side, and stands in the Tohoku region were younger. However, no clear difference among regions was detected.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">The hierarchical model that considers spatial structure enabled us to evaluate growth functions for each prefecture (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0570">Figure S7 and Figure S8</ce:cross-ref>) and further revealed the regional-level growth functions with the weighted means of the parameters (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0575">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig4"/> and <ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0580">Table S4</ce:cross-ref>). The model estimates suggested that <mml:math altimg="si29.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> in the Kanto region was significantly higher than that of all other regions, followed by that in the Tohoku region. In contrast, Chugoku and Kyushu (situated in the western part of Japan) had relatively low <mml:math altimg="si29.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>. No significant difference in <mml:math altimg="si30.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> was detected among the regions, and <mml:math altimg="si31.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>rgn</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> was indicated to be lower in western Japan. Regarding the parameters at the prefecture level, <mml:math altimg="si122.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, <mml:math altimg="si123.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, and <mml:math altimg="si124.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>prf</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> varied between 198.3 MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> and 281.1 MgC ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>, 0.0274 and 0.0369, and 0.401 and 0.572, respectively (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig5" id="crosref0585">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig5"/>, <ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0590">S7 and S8</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.3" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0090">Prediction of carbon stock in <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests in Japan</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">Depending on six scenarios (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0595">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>), the predicted future carbon stock in <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests from 2022 to 2112 varied (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0600">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig6"/>). In the scenario based on the YT model that assumed the current cut stem volume and reforestation rate (Case 1.1), forest area decreased by 56 % from 4.41 Mha in 2022 to 1.92 Mha in 2100 (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0605">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>a). In contrast, in the case using the NFI-LS model and the same management parameters (Case 2.1), the forest area decreased by 34 % to 2.93 Mha in 2100.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">Under the scenario based on the YT model with no management (Case 1.0), the carbon stock increased by 26 % from 469.0 TgC in 2022 to 593.1 TgC in 2100 (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0610">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>b). With the current cut stem volume and reforestation rate (Case 1.1), the carbon stock decreased by 61 % compared with that in 2022 and was predicted to be 181.0 TgC in 2100, reflecting the change in forest area. In the scenario using a 100 % reforestation rate instead of the current rate of 36.8 % (Case 1.2), the carbon stock declined by 22 % and was calculated to be 367.5 TgC in 2100. In contrast, carbon stock in 2022 estimated with the NFI-LS model was predicted to be 756.6 TgC, which was 61 % higher than that based on the YT model. The NFI-LS model-based simulation with no management (Case 2.0) predicted that the carbon stock would increase by 39 % and reaches 1052.0 TgC in 2100, whereas the scenario with the current management parameters (Case 2.1) predicted that the carbon stock would increase to 769.0 TgC around 2032 and thereafter decrease but still store as much carbon as under Case 1.0 even in 2100. The growth models based on both the YT and NFI-LS data (i.e., YT vs. NFI-LS models) resulted in more than 3 times greater differences in carbon stock estimates in 2100. The scenario based on the NFI-LS model with a 100 % reforestation rate (Case 2.2) predicted a carbon stock of 788.6 TgC in 2100, which was slightly higher than that in 2022 and remained relatively stable throughout the simulation.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec4" role="discussion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0095">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec4.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0100">Significant updates on forest growth functions covering old-aged forests</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">Using the meta-analysis integrating NFI and LS data, we re-evaluated the growth characteristics of <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan. The new growth model (NFI-LS model) is significantly different from the old model (YT model) that was based on outdated national forest inventory data mainly surveyed in the 1960s. In particular, the asymptotic upper limit (<mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>) in the NFI-LS model was 1.8 times higher than that in the YT model (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl2" id="crosref0615">Table 2</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0620">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>), strongly supporting the possibility of underestimation in forest carbon stock previously noted by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0625">Egusa et al. (2020)</ce:cross-ref>. Moreover, the NFI-LS model differed from the growth model for <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests based on the NFI3 data derived from forest surveys conducted in the period 2009–2013 (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib14" id="crosref0630">Egusa et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:cross-ref refid="bib14" id="crosref0635">Egusa et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref> established a growth model based on the same Richards function using only the NFI3 data (hereafter, NFI3 model), but these authors did not hierarchize the model into the prefecture and stand levels. In contrast to the NFI3 model, the NFI-LS model estimated <mml:math altimg="si17.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">d</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mo>_</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mi>max</mml:mi>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> to be 1.5 times higher, and <mml:math altimg="si18.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>k</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si19.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math>, which are related to the length of the growth periods for each forest stage, also differed. As a result, the ages of peaks carbon accumulation rate differed among the YT, NFI3, and NFI-LS models (18 yr, 7 yr, and 20 yr, respectively), and the onsets of the old-growth stage also differed (86 yr, 68 yr, and 113 yr, respectively). This indicates that <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests can continue to accumulate biomass longer than is currently predicted, and thus, forest management that incorporates longer periods is a possible option. Furthermore, although leaf and branch biomass tend to gradually decrease after the peak in the relatively early phase of forest development, as recognized in previous studies of <ce:italic>Picea abies</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib49" id="crosref0640">Mund et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib56" id="crosref0645">Ogawa, 2018</ce:cross-ref>), the growth period for stem biomass accrual is much longer than those for whole-tree biomass (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl2" id="crosref0650">Table 2</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0655">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>a and b). Importantly, from the perspective of wood production, the biomass accumulation pattern for the tree stems is a prime factor for determining logging plans to maximize forest stem volume per year (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib52" id="crosref0660">Nishizono, 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib55" id="crosref0665">Nishizono et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>), and logging practices with 45 yr intervals are the most rational at the national level, though in practice, local-specific rotation periods should be applied for each region according to the present results (<ce:cross-ref refid="tbl2" id="crosref0670">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">The reasons why the NFI-LS model differs from the YT model are as follows: 1) the lack of data on old-aged forests in original YT data, 2) improvement in the forest growth environment in recent decades, and 3) a decline in timber demand in recent decades (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0675">Egusa et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). In the 1960s, when the forest survey was conducted to generate the yield tables, most <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests were young, and few old-aged forests existed. Accordingly, forest biomass in the old-growth forests was likely estimated by extrapolation, which introduced substantial uncertainty. There have also been suggested positive effects of environmental changes on forest growth in recent decades including the roughly 100 ppm increase in atmospheric CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> concentration since 1960 (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib28" id="crosref0680">IPCC, 2023</ce:cross-ref>) enhancing carbon assimilation in plants (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0685">McMahon et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib82" id="crosref0690">Ueyama et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), the rise in nitrogen deposition into forest ecosystems (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib48" id="crosref0695">Morino et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>), and the lengthening of the growing season of plants within a year owing to global warming (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib5" id="crosref0700">Begović et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib19" id="crosref0705">Fang et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0710">McMahon et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>). Furthermore, the declining utilization of forest resources and importing of wood has allowed forests to maintain woody biomass accrual with limited impact from forestry practices (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib34" id="crosref0715">Jörgensen et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib40" id="crosref0720">Lin et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib52" id="crosref0725">Nishizono, 2010</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">The NFI3 model of <ce:cross-ref refid="bib14" id="crosref0730">Egusa et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref> somewhat overcame the aforementioned three factors because it used the recently acquired NFI3 data representing forest metrics from 2009 to 2013. However, the present study indicates that even the NFI3 model may underestimate carbon density in comparison to the NFI-LS model. This model distinction is explicitly attributed to integration of the LS data, which includes well-developed mature forests. Notably, it implies that the NFI survey, conducted at 4 km grid points across the Japanese archipelago, does not effectively reflect elite old-aged forests with high growth capacity. To exploit the full potential of carbon accumulation in current <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> forests in the mature stage, we must take intensively managed forests into consideration through full stand maturity. Integration of data for such elite old-aged forests from the literature survey extended the range of stand age and reduced uncertainty caused by the extrapolation. The present meta-analysis demonstrates the importance of old-aged forest data for prediction of overall forest growth patterns in the future (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0735">Ciais et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0740">Luyssaert et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">Another important addition to the NFI-LS model is the hierarchical structuring of spatial scales within the growth model to improve accuracy of the model estimation (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0745">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0750">Fig. S10</ce:cross-ref>). Some LS data provide consecutive plot data over several decades (e.g., <ce:cross-ref refid="bib43" id="crosref0755">Masaki et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>), which enhances the robustness of fitting forest growth functions. Fitting the growth functions for each forest stand and adjusting error distributions based on the gamma distribution determines growth patterns more accurately than developing the model with defined functions only for large spatial scales (i.e., national and regional levels) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0760">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0765">Nishizono et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). This approach was achieved by using data from the consecutive plots present in both NFI3 and NFI4, which are of higher quality than the previous NFI data. Fitting models for each stand enabled us to avoid misinterpretation of growth patterns owing to variance among forest stands caused by unknown factors. Hierarchical models are useful for the meta-analysis of data with hierarchical structures, such as a broad range of spatial scales from individuals to regional or national categories (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib86" id="crosref0770">Zhu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Notably, although hierarchical models using non-linear functions seem complex, a Bayesian approach is a powerful option to estimate their parameters, and thus, their widespread use is predicted to elucidate complex and comprehensive mechanisms of ecological systems.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">We acknowledge that the NFI-LS model did not explicitly account for the effects of forestry practices because field surveys for NFI were implemented without consideration of the forest history. However, management factors will be important for further refinement of the growth models. For example, some forest plots have experienced forestry practices such as thinning, while others have not, potentially leading to large differences in growth and stand biomass accrual. Although it is unclear to what extent such practices affect growth models, there are several possibilities. The first one is that carbon density decreases temporarily after thinning, and the carbon accumulation rate is negative between the periods before and after thinning. In fact, some negative values in the accumulation rate were calculated by comparing the NFI3 and NFI4 data in the consecutive plots (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0775">Fig. S4</ce:cross-ref>). In contrast, immediately after thinning, the growth environment of the remaining trees improves and carbon assimilation increases (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib38" id="crosref0780">Kunisaki et al., 1999</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib40" id="crosref0785">Lin et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib52" id="crosref0790">Nishizono, 2010</ce:cross-ref>). Thinned forests deviate from the original course of the growth pattern and take time to recover carbon stock (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib55" id="crosref0795">Nishizono et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>), or the maximum capacity for carbon density may decrease permanently (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib34" id="crosref0800">Jörgensen et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib40" id="crosref0805">Lin et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Importantly, such situations can be caused directly by artificial phenomena, such as thinning, and by disturbance owing to the occurrence of abnormal weather events in recent years (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib69" id="crosref0810">Seidl et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). In natural and old-growth forests, survival capacities such as shade tolerance of seedlings and sub-canopy trees can be a key factor that maximizes the potential of carbon accumulation and recovery from gap occurrence. To predict forest development with consideration of tree mortality resulting from self-thinning and natural disturbance, an individual-based model assuming individual tree biomass and stand density would be useful. Growth functions at an individual tree level should be integrated into forest growth models to evaluate carbon dynamics flexibly in response to significant disturbance.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">Climate change and human activities may also influence forest development patterns. Extreme climatic events are expected to intensify for the next several decades (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib16" id="crosref0815">Elsner et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib26" id="crosref0820">Hirabayashi et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>), and wood demand on the international market may affect its supply from each country. To adjust to such issues, forest growth functions for <ce:italic>C</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>japonica</ce:italic> and other important forest types should be updated. The motivation to renew yield tables for biomass estimation has increased (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib71" id="crosref0825">Shimada, 2010</ce:cross-ref>). Repeating NFI-type surveys across many countries would provide valuable information to clarify and predict changes in forest resources (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0830">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib11" id="crosref0835">Chen et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0840">Egusa et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib47" id="crosref0845">Molina-Valero et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib57" id="crosref0850">Ols et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib65" id="crosref0855">Repo et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib86" id="crosref0860">Zhu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Re-evaluation of forest resources and growth characteristics is feasible so long as NFI surveys are sustainably conducted in the future.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec4.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0105">Geographical variation in growth of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">Significant geographical variation in the growth characteristics of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests (<ce:cross-refs refid="fig4 fig5" id="crosrefs0015">Figs. 4 and 5</ce:cross-refs>) may be attributed to the unique environmental diversity of the Japanese archipelago (<ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0865">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>). Environmental gradients caused by climates and geographical features range widely across Japan and regulate forest development in each region (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib51" id="crosref0870">Nakao et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0875">Nishizono et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). The Japanese archipelago is distributed over a 15° latitudinal range, leading to broad variation in temperatures. Additionally, the northeast monsoon and the warm ocean current influence the climate, and these factors result in two distinct climates represented by the Sea of Japan side and the Pacific Ocean side in Japan, where mountains dominate (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib42" id="crosref0880">Maejima, 1967</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib81" id="crosref0885">Uemura, 1989</ce:cross-ref>). Such strong contrast leads to significant relationships between growth characteristics and environmental factors (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0890">Nishizono et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Using data from the 1st national forest inventory (NFI1), <ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0895">Nishizono et al. (2014)</ce:cross-ref> showed that maximum stand height and age relationships differ depending on the regional climate. Specifically, in regions that experience low temperatures, heavy snowfall, low solar radiation, and low precipitation in summer, forests have a low growth rate in the initial growth phase but reach a higher maximum stand height. In contrast, in regions with the opposite climatic conditions, forests grow relatively rapidly in the initial phase but attain a low maximum height. The former belonging to the Sea of Japan area is called “Ura-sugi”, while the latter belonging to the Pacific Ocean area is called “Omote-sugi”. Assuming positive relationships between maximum stand height and forest carbon density, the present results might support these previous findings. In the NFI-LS model, the high maximum mean carbon density in the southern Tohoku and Kanto regions reflects the growth characteristics of Ura-sugi, whereas relatively rapid growth rates and earlier maturity in Kyushu and Wakayama reflects the characteristics of Omote-sugi (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0900">Nishizono et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). In Europe, it has been suggested that summer precipitation has positive effects on the radial growth trends of trees based on tree-ring measurements (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib57" id="crosref0905">Ols et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), and warmer temperature in winter positively influences tree growth of <ce:italic>P</ce:italic>. <ce:italic>abies</ce:italic> in southern parts of its natural distribution (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib73" id="crosref0910">Suvanto et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). Given that the effects of global warming on growth environments have been observed in Japan (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib33" id="crosref0915">Japan Meteorological Agency, 2024</ce:cross-ref>), understanding of the variation in carbon accumulation patterns among local regions with environmental factors is needed.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">It is possible that both environmental and genotypic factors contribute to the geographical variation in growth characteristics of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests. Although we did not design an analytic approach that combines growth characteristics with these factors, local environmental factors may affect forest growth. However, the factors that control the high maximum carbon density in the southern Tohoku and Kanto regions are unclear. As <ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0920">Nishizono et al. (2014)</ce:cross-ref> indicated, a multivariate analysis will be required to elucidate the controlling factors. Given that the NFI data include both natural and artificial forests, the influences of genotypic differentiation among natural forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib80" id="crosref0925">Tsumura et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>) and of cultivars in plantation forests, as well as different planting techniques used in plantations cannot be ignored. In addition, even within the same mountain and watershed area, forest growth is affected by microtopography (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib17" id="crosref0930">Enoki et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib51" id="crosref0935">Nakao et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib77" id="crosref0940">Tange and Ge, 2020</ce:cross-ref>), which complicates the light, water, and nutrient conditions differentiating individual tree growth depending their shade and drought tolerance.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">Differences in forest growth patterns with geographical variation suggest that region-specific optimization of harvest periods and forestry practices is desirable (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib38" id="crosref0945">Kunisaki et al., 1999</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib52" id="crosref0950">Nishizono, 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib55" id="crosref0955">Nishizono et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>). For example, forests that undergo rapid growth in the initial stage in Kyushu should be cut earlier than in other regions, whereas forests with a high maximum carbon density can be exploited for production of large-diameter trees. Improvement in wood production efficiency will be expected by consideration of the variation in forest growth characteristics among regions and optimization of forest management.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec4.3" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0110">Prediction of forest carbon stock of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic>
                     </ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">Capturing how forest biomass accrual changes with stand age is fundamental to prediction of future forest carbon stocks (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0960">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib86" id="crosref0965">Zhu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). The present study predicted the <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forest area and carbon stock over the next 100 years based on different data sources and obtained distinct estimates with each data set (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0970">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>). To provide a constant supply of wood production every year under the current reforestation rate, the estimation based on the YT model (Case 1.1) concluded that a large percentage of the forest area will disappear by the end of this century (<ce:cross-ref refid="fig6" id="crosref0975">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>a). In contrast, the simulation with the NFI-LS model under the same management scenario (Case 2.1) indicates a reduction in forest area lost by half of that predicted with the YT model. Thus, underestimation of forest carbon density (with the YT model) can overestimate the reduction in forest area and available carbon stock and further hinder appropriate forest management for wood supply.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0260" view="all">The carbon stock in forests in 2022 based on the NFI-LS model was estimated to be 756.6 TgC, which is much higher than that (approximately 622 TgC in 2011) estimated based on the NFI3 model by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib14" id="crosref0980">Egusa et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref>. Surprisingly, in Case 2.0 assuming no management, the carbon stock of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan will exceed 1000 TgC in 2100, which indicates that <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests have the capacity to accumulate approximately 300 TgC by 2100. Although, as Case 1.0 indicates, <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests have been considered to have little potential to accumulate carbon and to be of harvesting age, the management plan might require reconsideration. When using the current cut volume and reforestation rate (Case 2.1), the carbon stock was predicted to increase for several years but thereafter decrease until 2100. However, when assuming a reforestation rate of 100 % (Case 2.2), the carbon stock was predicted to remain stable or increase slightly for the entire period. This scenario enables continuation of the wood supply while maintaining forest carbon resources. The present results suggest that the <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests of Japan have strong potential to accumulate more carbon resources than previously predicted and that sustainable use of wood resources can be achieved by appropriate forest management.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0265" view="all">The Japanese government has indicated that it aims to achieve a domestic supply of timber that accounts for more than 50 % of national needs which would necessitate increasing domestic timber supply from 31 Mm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> in 2019 to 42 Mm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> in 2030 (J<ce:cross-ref refid="bib32" id="crosref0985">apan Forestry Agency, 2011</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib31" id="crosref0990">2021</ce:cross-ref>). In addition, the government has set a goal to become a carbon-neutral country, which offsets greenhouse gas emissions by their absorption within the country, by 2050 (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib29" id="crosref0995">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023a</ce:cross-ref>). Given that <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> is the most important species in the timber industry in Japan, the present findings provide positive scientific evidence regarding the feasibility of the current governmental plans. Assuming 28.3 Mm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> as the annual cut stem volume in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests, only two-thirds of the annual increment in stem volume is used currently. Therefore, <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests have sufficient growth capacity to supply additional wood to improve the timber self-sufficient rate. It is recommended that the government should base future decisions on these findings to promote sustainable forest supply and resource management.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0270" view="all">Japan contains one of the largest forest carbon pools in east Asia owing to the high ratio of the forest to non-forest area (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib20" id="crosref1000">Fang et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>). In particular, <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests have the largest carbon stock among all forest types (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref1005">Egusa et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), and thus, predicting the carbon stocks in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests largely influences the carbon stock estimate in Japan's total forests. According to the present results, <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests show a strong growth capacity to accumulate substantial carbon even in old-aged stands. Although we cannot draw a direct comparison because necromass was not included in the present estimates, the maximum carbon density seems to be higher than that of major broadleaved forests and some coniferous forests and is considered to be comparable to that of fir and spruce forests in the United States (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref1010">Barnett et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). Further, the maximum carbon density may be approximately twice that of Norway spruce (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib49" id="crosref1015">Mund et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib63" id="crosref1020">Pretzsch et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>) and boreal forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib65" id="crosref1025">Repo et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Construction of carbon offset systems through carbon credits has been promoted worldwide (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib3" id="crosref1030">Badgley et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib15" id="crosref1035">Ellerman et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib29" id="crosref1040">Japan Forestry Agency, 2023a</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib45" id="crosref1045">Michaelowa et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). In Japan, annual CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> absorption in forests is estimated based on stand age classes as a simplified procedure. The present study implies that CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> absorption in each stand age class may be higher than expected so far and that re-evaluation of forest carbon density with age will accelerate carbon credit trading. To maximize the benefits from forest resources, optimization of forest management by reference to region-specific forest growth characteristics, including shade and drought tolerance of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic>
                        <ce:bold>
                           <ce:italic>,</ce:italic>
                        </ce:bold> and improvement in the reforestation rate are essential factors in maintaining wood supply and forest carbon resources. In future studies, additional forestry parameters, such as harvest period, yield stem volume, and reforestation rate, should be considered to determine the best forestry practices for optimal forest management. Prediction of carbon stock in forest ecosystems is fundamental for forest administrators and political decision-makers to achieve a carbon-neutral society.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec5" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0115">Conclusions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0275" view="all">The growth model for <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests based on the most recent NFI and LS data (NFI-LS model) differed significantly from the model based on outdated yield tables (YT model), suggesting that the maximum carbon density was 1.8 times higher and the stand age at the onset of the old-growth stage was 1.3 times older. Thus, the growth potential of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests has been underestimated in recent decades owing to the lack of old-aged forest data and conflicts between previous and current growth environments. The growth model used for forest resource predictions and management should be updated with a suitable data set and appropriate model design because it may be affected by ongoing climate changes and human activities.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0280" view="all">Geographical variation in the growth model parameters was revealed with the hierarchical Bayesian model framework. In particular, a parameter representing the maximum forest carbon density varied substantially among regions, suggesting general trends of higher and lower accumulation capacity in eastern and western Japan, respectively. The unique environmental diversity of Japanese archipelago results in geographical variation in the forest growth characteristics, and therefore, region-specific optimization of forestry practices is desirable to maximize forest carbon accumulation and wood production.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0285" view="all">Simulations for current and future carbon stocks of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests based on the present growth model (NFI-LS model) suggested positive results. <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests across Japan can accumulate more than 1000 TgC by 2100, assuming the scenario of no forest management (Case 2.0). Even if the current annual wood cut volume is maintained, carbon stocks in <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests would remain stable at more than 750 TgC throughout the present century under a consistent forest area (Case 2.2). In conclusion, <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forests have strong potential to accumulate additional carbon resources, and sustainable use of wood resources can be achieved by appropriate forest management. The present findings provide supporting evidence to enhance the value of <ce:italic>C. japonica</ce:italic> forest resources across Japan and increase the feasibility of a carbon-neutral society in the country.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec6" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0120">CRediT authorship contribution statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0290" view="all">
                     <ce:bold>Ryo Nakahata:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Writing – original draft, Funding acquisition, Formal analysis, Data curation. <ce:bold>Tomohiro Egusa:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Data curation. <ce:bold>Tomo'omi Kumagai:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Funding acquisition, Conceptualization.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0010" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0125">Declaration of competing interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0295" view="all">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ack0010" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0130">Acknowledgments</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0300" view="all">We thank Dr. L. McCormack and members of the Laboratory of Root Biology in Center for Tree Science, The Morton Arboretum, for reviewing our manuscript before submission. This study was funded in part by grants from <ce:grant-sponsor id="gs1" sponsor-id="https://doi.org/10.13039/501100001691" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Japan Society for the Promotion of Science</ce:grant-sponsor> (<ce:grant-sponsor id="gs2" sponsor-id="https://doi.org/10.13039/501100001691" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">JSPS</ce:grant-sponsor>): nos. 23KJ0321 to RN and 21H05316 to TK.</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
